        "FIGREF0": {
            "text": "described 18 out of 88 COVID-19 patients hospitalized in the Lecco Hospital (Lombardy region, Italy) 55 who developed erythematous rash (n=14), widespread urticaria (n=3) or varicella-like vesicles (n=1). 5 56 During the Italian outbreak, we have observed a varicella-like papulovesicular exanthem as a rare but 57 specific COVID-19-associated skin manifestation. Eight Italian Dermatology Units collected clinical 58 data of patients with COVID-19 (microbiologically proven by nasopharyngeal swab) and no history of 59 new medications in the previous 15 days who developed varicella-like lesions. 60 Demographic and clinical features of the 22 patients are summarized in",
            "latex": null,
            "type": "figure"
        },
        "FIGREF1": {
            "text": "61Male patients were 72.7% (n=16/22) and the median age was 60 years. Most patients (n=17/22; 62 77.3%) came from Lombardy, currently the worst-hit region in Italy, while the remaining patients 63 came from Piedmont (n=1), Emilia-Romagna (n=1), Toscana (n=1), Lazio (n=1), and Campania (n=1). 64Median latency time from systemic symptoms to exanthem was three days (range from -2 to 12 65 days). Median duration of skin manifestations was eight days (range= 4 -15 days). Lesions were 66 scattered in most cases (n=16; 72.7%), while they were diffuse in six (27.3%) cases. Predominance of 67 vesicles was observed in 12 (54.5%) patients. No variations in the papulovesicular presentation were 68 observed in our case series. Trunk was constantly involved, in some cases in association with limbs 69 (n=4; 18.2%).(Fig. 1a-d)No facial or mucosal involvements were scored. Itching, which was generally 70 mild, was reported in nine (40.9%) patients. In all the patients who underwent skin biopsy (n=7), 71 histology was consistent with viral infection.(Fig. 1e-f) 72",
            "latex": null,
            "type": "figure"
        },
        "TABREF0": {
            "text": "The novel coronavirus disease, an infection due to the severe acute respiratory syndrome 48 coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2) that may cause interstitial pneumonia and respiratory failure, has 49 currently taken on pandemic proportions. 1 COVID-19 outbreak has emerged in Wuhan (China) and 50 has rapidly spread to Europe, particularly to Italy 2 , where, as of to date (April 1, 2020), 80572 people 51 Two recent publications have brought attention to COVID-19-associated cutaneous manifestations. 4,5 53",
            "latex": null,
            "type": "table"
        },
        "TABREF1": {
            "text": "Its typical features are constant trunk involvement, usually scattered 79 distribution and mild/absent pruritus, the latter being in line with most viral exanthems but unlike 80 true varicella. Lesions generally appear 3 days after systemic symptoms and disappear upon 8 days, 81 without leaving scarring. A limitation of our study was missing histology in some cases. Moreover, 82 demonstration of SARS-CoV-2 presence by Polymerase Chain Reaction in lesional skin was not 83 possible due to specific primer unavailability. If further studies validate our findings, this early skin 84 manifestation will represent a useful clue to suspect COVID-19 in asymptomatic/paucisymptomatic 85 The authors wish to thank the following collaborators for their help in data collection and patients' Marica Annunziata, Cristiana Colonna, Massimo Ghislanzoni, Raffaele Gianotti, Chiara Moltrasio, Gianluca Nazzaro, Emanuela Passoni, Marina Picca, Gaetano Rizzitelli, Diego Tosi Demographic and clinical data of patients with varicella-like exanthem associated with COVID-19 110",
            "latex": null,
            "type": "table"
        }
